# zero-arena-bacend — ORACLE service only.
# Copy this into `.env` on the host that runs `bacend oracle serve`.
# The oracle service does NOT need any dataset / Binance / wallet config.
#
# What this service does: HTTP signer for ERC-7857 re-encryption proofs.
# An SDK consumer calls `transferAgent(...)` → their `HttpOracleClient`
# POSTs to this service → this service signs with ORACLE_PRIVATE_KEY and
# returns the signature. The key NEVER leaves this process.
#
# Threat model in v0.1: this is a trusted stub. Run it on infrastructure
# you control. v0.4 replaces this with a TEE-attested signer inside 0G
# Compute Sealed Inference — the protocol does not change.
#
# Chain-agnostic: this service signs over the chainId in the request body.
# The on-chain `ReencryptionOracle.signer()` is what pins the trust root.

# ─── Oracle signer ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Key matching the on-chain `ReencryptionOracle.signer()` address. If these
# diverge, the iNFT contract will reject every transfer signature this
# service produces. Compare against `cast call <ORACLE_ADDR> "signer()"`
# after boot.
ORACLE_PRIVATE_KEY=

# HTTP bind. 0.0.0.0 for container deployments; 127.0.0.1 to keep it on the loopback.
ORACLE_HOST=0.0.0.0
ORACLE_PORT=8787

# Optional bearer-token gate. If set, callers of POST /sign-transfer-proof
# must include `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. Strongly recommended for
# anything not on localhost.
# ORACLE_AUTH_TOKEN=
